					<div class="bio">
						<h4>Howard Bryant</h4>
												<p>Howard Bryant is a senior writer for ESPN.com and <em>ESPN the Magazine</em> and has served as the sports correspondent for NPR’s <em>Weekend Edition Saturday</em> since 2006. He is the author of <em>The Last Hero: A Life of Henry Aaron</em>; <em>Juicing the Game: Drugs, Power, and the Fight for the Soul of Major League Baseball</em>; <em>Shut Out: A Story of Race and Baseball in Boston</em>; and the three-book Legends sports series for middle-grade readers. His most recent book is <em>The Heritage: Black Athletes, a Divided America, and the Politics of Patriotism</em>. A two-time Casey Award winner (2003, 2011) for best baseball book of the year, Bryant was also a 2003 finalist for the Society for American Baseball Research Seymour Medal. In 2016, he was a finalist for the National Magazine Award and received the 2016 Salute to Excellence Award from the National Association of Black Journalists. He lives in Northampton, Massachusetts.</p>
